<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> When black children see people who look like them, what do they see them doing? They see high-profile sportsmen and sportswomen, they see musicians and actors. They don't see accountants, scientists or doctors.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
On the idea of affirmative action, or positive discrimination, or whatever you choose to call it...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Doesn't that introduce the danger of tokenism?</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
People said the same thing about promoting women in science. The truth is there's no perfect solution. In the US, even if the first group of black people got in as a token, the fact that they were there in sufficient numbers to have an impact meant that the next group of blacks to walk through the door were there on merit.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
If rolemodels are important, then it makes a good argument in favour of affirmative action. Sucks to be in Dalamarn's position, but if it's what is needed to &quot;break the glass ceiling&quot; or whatever, then it has merit. If this is the reason behind the policies, then they aren't needed indefinately however.<br>
<br>
What happened 300 years ago isn't the end of the problem. Here in Australia,  there are many aboriginal people who recall not even being counted as people on a census, let alone being allowed to vote. Such issues might not exist today, but I believe it would take several generations for the social and economic damage to be mitigated.<br>
<br>
Racial profiling happens. A <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.policeforum.org/racial/RBP_2.pdf">police survey</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->(pdf) shows that most police think it is not a problem. However, 40% think that it is a problem to at least some extent, and most believe that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> the community they police</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> view it as at least some sort of problem. Toward the other end of the spectrum of viewpoints, <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.aclu.org/profiling/report/">here is an ACLU report</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->.   The &quot;truth&quot; as to how bad the problem is probably lies somewhere in the middle.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Today, blacks constitute 13 percent of the country's drug users; 37 percent of those arrested on drug charges; 55 percent of those convicted; and 74 percent of all drug offenders sentenced to prison.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
That info is lacking in data as to what the nature of the charges and convictions are, but some possible interpretations: 55% convicted to 74% imprisoned could mean that blacks are getting harsher sentancing, or that whites commit less serious crimes which don't result in prison sentances. 37% arrested to 55% convicted could mean that whites are more likely to be let off, or that they are actually more likely to be wrongly arrested. 55/37 = roughly 50% greater conviction rate for blacks who are arrested. 37/13 = almost triple the arrest rate for blacks. <p>----------------------------------<br>
